From: Hal Nash <HNASH@wwcc.cc.wy.us>
Date: Thu, 2 Oct 1997 10:37:20 -0600

The question offered at the end of this posting is incisive and, far from
being rhetorical, is worthy of attention and serious consideration. Changes
in human behavior and/or changes wrought by humans have frequently resulted
in microbial shifts, sometimes resulting in disease. At least a partial
answer to the question is contained within the question itself: "If the
genesis of this disease . . . was a change in the operational technology of
the animal rendering industry".
The recognition of a change in the way things have been done, or the degree
to which they depart from the way nature has done things should send up a
red flag to us. The use of offal as feed for a strictly herbivorous animal
is both a change in how bovines feed and a change in how humans have done
it in the past 10,000 years.
That technology seems to me to have been a radical change or departure. And
we have gotten a microbial reaction. When a revolution in our thoughts
regarding sexual behavior occurred in the US in the late 60s and through
the 70s, the microbes responded to that change (and I'm not just talking
about HIV). Radical changes occurred in behaviors and the microbes were
there to take advantage of the changes. As human behavior changes, we can
expect microbes to change also.
Evaluation of the changes proposed must come before the changes are
enacted. We might not be able to accurately predict exactly what will
happen. What we can definitely expect is a microbial reaction to our actions.
What else is happening out there in terms of humans changing things around?
Is the incidence of food borne outbreaks in the US due to and increase in
food-borne microbes, increased virulence, or is it due to the fact that
lots more people go out to eat now. Or, is it a two-way street, both
humans and microbes feeling each other out, each trying to figure out what
the other is going to do. (Apologies for the anthropomorphism here.)
There are probably changes going on out there that we are not even
conscious of, but can recognize if we ask the right questions. I hate
buzzwords, but perhaps it's time to be proactive and head off any changes
occurring that spell disaster at some point in the future.
[The tricky bit is to identify which changes are going to cause problems.
If something might cause a problem, will the problem(s) be minor or
something big enough so that we should halt a new innovation? - Mod. pc
